class Solution {
    public int numWays(int steps, int arrLen) {
        int MOD = (int) (1e9 + 7);
        arrLen = Math.min(arrLen, steps + 1);
        int[] dp = new int[arrLen];
        dp[0] = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i <= steps; i++) {
            int[] next = new int[arrLen];
            for (int j = 0; j < arrLen; j++) {
                next[j] = dp[j];
                if (j > 0) next[j] = (next[j] + dp[j - 1]) % MOD;
                if (j < arrLen - 1) next[j] = (next[j] + dp[j + 1]) % MOD;
            }
            dp = next;
        }
        return dp[0];
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(steps * min(arrLen, steps))
space complexity: O(min(arrLen, steps))
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Dynamic programming is used to track the number of ways to reach each position. The state dp[j] represents the number of ways to reach index j. The next state is calculated based on the current state and the possible moves (left, right, stay). The result is returned modulo 10^9 + 7 to avoid overflow.
